                    </div>
                    <span>Quintessential guide to obtaining and maintaining political power. Written in the 16th Century, The Prince remains one of the most read sources for would-be world leaders.  A must read for any political science or history major.  </span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">5 Centuries Old, but Still Applicable</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>1</span>
                      /
                      <span>1</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-03-25</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>The Prince is a primer in how a new Prince should govern his new territory.  It is seen as having frequent parallels in the business world.  
<br />
<br />Any book that has been in print continuously for 500 years has to have something going for it. The Prince is a set of rules that Machiavelli would have the Prince follow. They have entered our culture as a set of sayings such as "it is better to be loved & feared, it is better to be feared then loved, it is dangerous to be held in contempt or hatred." 
<br />
<br />By today's standards his recommendations are pretty brutal, Saddam Hussein would have found them to be exactly what he followed. Our elected princes (or our princes in business) in the US can't be quite this rough. Perhaps if we use the word fire rather than kill when a new president comes into the Government or the Corporation. 
<br />
<br />Machiavelli was a better writer and observer than he was a practicioner. He wrote the book while in prison for picking the wrong prince to back.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">The Prince</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>0</span>
                      /
                      <span>2</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-03-20</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>The Prince is what Niccolo Machiavelli believes what a prince should act like.  It is basically a template for how you should rule your kingdom.  He has several pieces of funny yet good advice.   Such as, if the noble should cause you trouble, strip him of all of his land and title and ship him out of your country.  He talks about the characteristics a good prince would have.  A prince must be merciful, yet cruel.  This way he is viewed as a merciful yet stern prince.  If you were to rule a monarcy and you wanted to hold on to it, the best way to do this is to follow the template in the prince.  </span>
                  
              
